    line-height: 1.6;">Можешь обьяснить что он тут написал <br/>To resume RVC training, follow these steps:<br/><br/>Backup the entire &quot;/logs/&quot; folder when done training on Colab, for the first run at least. Ensure you have both necessary files for resuming training (config.json and the pre-processed wav folders... not backed up by default using the &#x27;save big file&#x27; option, unfortunately.)<br/>During retraining, use the same name (with the same capitalization) and sample rate (default is 40kHz if unchanged).<br/>Do not re-process the files unless you are missing the necessary folders (even then it may not work). Basically, avoid pressing &quot;process data&quot; or performing &quot;pitch extraction&quot; again.<br/>Only keep the two latest .pth files in the /logs/ folder for the model, based on their date modified. If there is a &quot;233333&quot; file, it represents the latest checkpoint, if you ticked ‘Save only latest ckpt’. Remove all other older .pth files, not based on their names, to avoid inaccuracies.<br/>Now you can start training again by pressing &#x27;train model&#x27;, with the same batch size as before. If the training starts from the beginning again, immediately use CTRL+C to stop the console server and try starting again.<br/>Be cautious when using the &quot;save only latest ckpt&quot; option; don&#x27;t turn it off if you had it on at first, and vice versa. If you turn it off on the next training run, the system will assume the &quot;23333&quot; file is the latest, and it missing may confuse it and make the pth set not detected by RVC. Renaming may help remedy this?<br/>If necessary, copy the pth file set and set a higher number (can be anything I think as long as both match) so it has a higher chance of &#x27;picking up&#x27; on the weights in the folder, if renaming doesn&#x27;t work</div><br/><br/>LLM response:<br/><div style="
    background-color: #fff3e6;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>The author is providing instructions on how to resume training on RVC (an audio classification model) by following several steps. These steps include backing up the entire "/logs/" folder after the first run, using the same name and sample rate for retraining, avoiding reprocessing the files unless necessary, keeping only the two latest .pth files in the /logs/ folder, restarting the training by pressing 'train model' with the same batch size, being cautious when using the "save only latest ckpt" option, and copying the pth file set and setting a higher number if renaming doesn't work. The instructions aim to avoid inaccuracies and confusion in the system during the resume training process.</p></div>

