    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>To prove that $g$ is quasi-concave, we need to show that its upper level sets are convex. That is, for any $t \in \mathbb{R}$, the set $U_t = {(x_1,x_2,x_3) \in \mathbb{R}^3 : g(x_1,x_2,x_3) \geq t}$ is convex.</p>
<p>First, we note that $-f(x_1,x_2,x_3) \leq 0$ for any $(x_1,x_2,x_3) \in \mathbb{R}^3$, since $f$ is defined as a sum of squares minus linear terms. Therefore, $g(x_1,x_2,x_3) \leq 0$ as well.</p>
<p>Now, let $(x_1,x_2,x_3)$ and $(y_1,y_2,y_3)$ be two points in $U_t$, i.e., $g(x_1,x_2,x_3) \geq t$ and $g(y_1,y_2,y_3) \geq t$. We want to show that the line segment connecting these two points is also contained in $U_t$.</p>
<p>Consider the function $h(u) = g(u x_1 + (1-u) y_1, u x_2 + (1-u) y_2, u x_3 + (1-u) y_3)$. Since $g$ is defined as the cube of $-f$, we have $g(x) = (-f(x))^3$, so $h(u) = (-f(u x_1 + (1-u) y_1, u x_2 + (1-u) y_2, u x_3 + (1-u) y_3))^3$. </p>
<p>Now, we observe that $-f$ is a convex function, since it is defined as a sum of squares minus linear terms. Therefore, by Jensen's inequality for convex functions, we have $-f(u x_1 + (1-u) y_1, u x_2 + (1-u) y_2, u x_3 + (1-u) y_3) \leq u (-f(x_1,x_2,x_3)) + (1-u) (-f(y_1,y_2,y_3))$. Taking the cube of both sides, we get $h(u) \geq t$, which shows that $(u x_1 + (1-u) y_1, u x_2 + (1-u) y_2, u x_3 + (1-u) y_3) \in U_t$. Since this is true for any $u \in [0,1]$, we conclude that the line segment connecting $(x_1,x_2,x_3)$ and $(y_1,y_2,y_3)$ is contained in $U_t$, and hence $U_t$ is convex.</p>
<p>Therefore, $g$ is quasi-concave.</p></div>

