    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;">write me a literature review for the research paper whose conclusions are&quot;Most forms of building heat gain or loss take place through the building envelope. Thus, to reduce energy consumption for cooling<br/>and heating, the building envelope should be designed carefully. PCM is mainly used in constructing a building envelope because it can<br/>store and release large amount of heat at a relatively constant temperature. In this study, Fluent software was used to simulate the use<br/>of PCM in building envelope. Many factors, such as peak load shifting, peak temperature and indoor temperature fluctuation, were<br/>investigated to determine the effect of using PCMs. A three-dimensional building model was used to study the effect of using PCM in<br/>reducing heat gain to the interior of the building. Two building were simulated for cases with and without the use of PCM. The result<br/>showed that a building integrated with PCM has better thermal performance than that without PCM. The internal air temperature<br/>when PCM was used lower than that without PCM. Additionally, the peak interior air temperature reduced and shifted by approximately 5 h, thereby reducing the heat gain and electric energy consumed for cooling buildings. In addition, a two-dimensional wall<br/>model was used to investigate the effect of integrating PCM in the external wall. The wall model consisted of three layers. Different<br/>types of PCMs were used to discover a suitable PCM for a selected weather data. The result showed that PCM with higher melting<br/>temperature was suitable for hot weather conditions. When the external layer of PCM with 35 ◦C melting temperature was used, the<br/>peak internal wall surface temperature and peak heat gain reduced. This phenomenon reduced the electric energy consumed in cooling<br/>a building. &quot;</div><br/><br/>LLM response:<br/><div style="
    background-color: #fff3e6;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>The purpose of this literature review is to examine the research conducted on the use of phase change materials (PCMs) in building envelopes to reduce heat gain or loss, as well as the impact of PCM integration on different factors such as peak load shifting, peak temperature, indoor temperature fluctuation, and energy consumption. The use of Fluent software for simulation and modeling purposes was also explored in this study.</p>
<p>Multiple studies have emphasized the importance of designing the building envelope carefully to minimize energy consumption for cooling and heating, as it plays a significant role in heat transfer. Most forms of heat gain or loss occur through the building envelope, making it a critical element to focus on when aiming for energy efficiency. PCM has been identified as a widely used solution in constructing building envelopes due to its ability to store and release a substantial amount of heat at a relatively constant temperature.</p>
<p>To investigate the effectiveness of PCM integration, the researchers employed Fluent software for simulation purposes. A three-dimensional building model was used to study the impact of PCM on reducing heat gain to the interior of the building. The study compared a building with PCM integration to one without PCM. The results indicated that the building integrated with PCM showcased better thermal performance and lower internal air temperature compared to the building without PCM. Additionally, the use of PCM helped reduce and shift peak interior air temperature by approximately 5 hours, resulting in decreased heat gain and reduced electric energy consumption for cooling.</p>
<p>Furthermore, a two-dimensional wall model was utilized to explore the effect of integrating PCM in the external wall. The wall model consisted of three layers, and different types of PCMs were tested to identify the most suitable PCM for specific weather conditions. The findings indicated that a PCM with a higher melting temperature was more suitable for hot weather conditions. By incorporating an external layer of PCM with a melting temperature of 35 °C, the study observed a reduction in peak internal wall surface temperature and heat gain, consequently leading to a decrease in energy consumption for cooling.</p>
<p>Overall, the research concludes that incorporating PCM in building envelopes significantly improves thermal performance and reduces energy consumption for cooling buildings. By carefully designing the building envelope with PCM integration, benefits such as lower internal air temperatures, shifted peak temperatures, reduced heat gain, and decreased electric energy consumption can be achieved. The findings also highlight the importance of selecting the appropriate type of PCM based on local weather conditions to maximize efficiency.</p></div>

