    line-height: 1.6;">Make a sequel proposal for Game of Thrones set 300 years after the series. Elizabeth Debicki plays protagonist, who seeks to make the Crown (with the Iron Throne, well, melted by Drogon) the real force in the realm as Queen Aurola Hightower. Have it be inspired by Europe c. 1700 and the decline of the PLC much like how Game of Thrones was inspired by the War of the Roses. Deconstruct the end of Season 8 by portraying the elective monarchy as weak and dominated by powerful feudal magnates (and rapacious ones as well). Queen Hightower was elected by the other magnates of Westeros but is not someone willing to play second fiddle, even if the Kingdom of the North and the various Free Cities benefits from such an arrangement, much like how the division of the HRE and the weakness of Poland-Lithuania suited Russia, Sweden, and Austria just fine in our timeline. While the characters of GoT are long dead, their legacies live on. Aurola is supposedly a Blackfyre from her mother’s side, with how her mother is Essosi. She could choose to reign from Oldtown, seat of her house, with the state of King&#x27;s Landing and how it hasn&#x27;t fully recovered from Daenerys burning it. King&#x27;s Landing would be the center of the High Septon, like how Rome as it devolved from a city of a million to a series of villages amidst ruins became the seat of the Pope after the fall of the Roman Empire.<br/></div><br/><br/>LLM response:<br/><div style="
    background-color: #fff3e6;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>Title: Game of Thrones: Rise of the Hightower</p>
<p>Synopsis:</p>
<p>Set 300 years after the events of Game of Thrones, the realm of Westeros has evolved into a shaky elective monarchy, inspired by Europe c. 1700 and the decline of the Polish-Lithuanian Commonwealth. The Iron Throne has long been melted by Drogon, and the once-powerful Kingdom of the North, along with the Free Cities, have gained prominence due to the increasing weakness of the Westeros monarchy. King's Landing has yet to fully recover from the devastation wrought by Daenerys Targaryen, and has transformed into a center of the High Septon, reminiscent of Rome during the fall of the Roman Empire.</p>
<p>In this new era of instability, Queen Aurola Hightower, portrayed by Elizabeth Debicki, is elected to the Crown by the powerful feudal magnates of Westeros. However, Queen Aurola is not content to merely play second fiddle in this flawed system. With her supposed Blackfyre lineage from her Essosi mother's side, she seeks to consolidate her power and restore the Crown as the true force in the realm.</p>
<p>Choosing to reign from Oldtown, the seat of House Hightower, Queen Aurola must navigate the treacherous political landscape of Westeros while evading the machinations of the noble houses that have benefited from the weakened state of the Crown. As her ambitions grow, she begins to draw upon the legacies of long-dead characters from the original series, learning from their successes and failures in her quest to unite Westeros under a single, powerful rule.</p>
<p>As tensions rise between the Crown and the noble houses, Westeros teeters on the brink of another bloody conflict, with the ever-present threat of the Kingdom of the North and the various Free Cities seeking to take advantage of the chaos. Queen Aurola Hightower must rally her allies, outwit her enemies, and forge a new destiny for herself and the realm, proving that the fire of the dragons still burns bright in the blood of House Hightower.</p>
<p>Game of Thrones: Rise of the Hightower is a tale of ambition, intrigue, and power, exploring the consequences of a divided Westeros and the lengths one ruler will go to in order to bring a shattered realm back to its former glory. Like its predecessor, the series will draw upon historical references and expertly weave them into a richly-textured, fantastical world, while also deconstructing the perceived victories and resolutions from the end of Season 8, ensuring that this new chapter in the Game of Thrones saga is as gripping as the original.</p></div>

